      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry insight\n\nThe Pb²⁺–Cl⁻ system is one of the most extensively studied metal–halide equilibria, owing to lead's environmental and geochemical importance. The log K ≈ 1.07 at *I* = 0.1 M reflects a moderately weak 1:1 complex — typical for a large, soft metal ion pairing with a hard halide. The sheer number of independent studies (electrochemical, spectroscopic, calorimetric) over six decades attests to the system's role as a benchmark for validating new experimental techniques in solution chemistry.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (Standard Reference Database 46 — Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
